B. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                         FY 2025     FY 2026       FY 2027
This effort develops and demonstrates technology to increase military utility. This is achieved by improving turbine engine
operational reliability, durability, mission flexibility, and performance while reducing weight, fuel consumption, and cost of
ownership. This includes demonstrator engines that address military specific needs for manned systems, autonomous vehicles
and munitions applications. This effort also focuses on integration of inlets, nozzles, engine-to-airframe compatibility, and power
and thermal management subsystems technologies.

FY 2026 Plans:
In FY 2025 and FY2026 the funding and work was executed in Project 634921 Aircraft Propulsion Subsystems Int. FY 2025
funding was $20.200 million and FY 2026 funding is $19.952 million.
FY 2027 Plans:
Continue new engine technologies to deliver reduced takeoff length, increased range, loiter, combat maneuverability, and lower
cost for affordable unmanned aerial systems in contested environments.
- Activities include design and development of augmentor test rigs.

Complete advanced propulsion air frame integration experiments to enable embedded propulsion systems for affordable mass via
embedded turbine engine propulsion.
- Activities include completion of model Based Systems Engineering for capturing advanced augmentor impacts to embedded fans
and advanced augmentor preliminary design review.

Commence augmentor technology development and demonstrations to reduce takeoff length and increase combat
maneuverability.
Activities include:
- Manufacturing of special test equipment and fixtures, buying and installing instrumentation to measure effectiveness, and
assembling augmentor technology.
