Description: This effort is not a new start. In FY 2027, the High-Speed Systems Integration and Demonstration effort and
associated funding transferred within this Program Element from Project 634926 / High Speed Systems Integ & Demo to Project
634920 / Flight Vehicle Tech Integration (now called Aerospace Systems Integration and Demonstration), to provide Congress
with improved understanding and traceability of the discrete Aerospace Systems technology areas in Research, Development,
Test & Evaluation (RDT&E), Air Force, Budget Activity (BA) 3.

This effort develops, demonstrates, and integrates weapon and platform (vehicle) aero, structural, power & thermal management,
and mission systems technologies to enable and improve the performance of future high-speed and hypersonic systems. Efforts
enable the development of feasible requirements, identify tech gaps and guide S&T investment, expand design and analysis
capabilities for reusable and expendable high-speed/hypersonic vehicle concepts, improve operability during maneuvers and
extended operating time, design long-range, responsive strike systems capable of take-off and landing, enable development of
long-range, hypersonic multi-Mach propulsion systems which support responsive strike capability with improved acceleration and
cruise efficiencies.

FY 2026 Plans:
In FY 2025 and FY 2026, the High-Speed Systems Integration and Demonstration effort and funding were reported in Program
Element 0603211F / Aerospace Technology Dev/Demo /Project 634926 / High Speed Systems Integ & Demo. FY 2025 funding
was $8.878 million and FY 2026 funding is $30.834 million.
FY 2027 Plans:
Continue technology maturation activities to investigate performance capabilities of responsive strike hypersonic platforms.
- Activities include demonstrating improved performance, thermal management, structural feasibility, and operability at higher
Mach speeds, advancing toward more affordable, reusable high-speed systems.

Continue high-speed airframe propulsion integration technology development focused on inlet and nozzle configurations, high-
speed propulsion dual-mode scramjet and the necessary high temperature seals and actuation methods.
- Activities include developing platform conceptual designs and conducting trade studies to refine analytical solutions for ground-
test evaluation, advancing high-speed dual-mode scramjet design and tools to optimize heat-release and distortion performance,
and performing trade studies to improve the efficiency and accuracy of high-speed direct-connect engine testing.

Continue technology development addressing aerodynamic challenges encountered by a durable hypersonic platform operating
across a wide Mach range.



