B. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                       FY 2025     FY 2026       FY 2027
Description: This effort is not a new start. In FY 2027, the High-Speed Propulsion Integration and Demonstration effort and
associated funding transferred within this Program Element from Project 634926 / High Speed Systems Integ & Demo to Project
634920 / Flight Vehicle Tech Integration (now called Aerospace Systems Integration and Demonstration), to provide Congress
with improved understanding and traceability of the discrete Aerospace Systems technology areas in Research, Development,
Test & Evaluation (RDT&E), Air Force, Budget Activity (BA) 3.

Develop and demonstrate, via ground and flight tests, the scramjet propulsion cycle to a technology readiness level appropriate
for full integration with other engine cycles (including turbine and rocket-based) to provide the Air Force with transformational
military capabilities. Multi-cycle engines will provide the propulsion systems for possible application to support aircraft and weapon
platforms. Efforts include scramjet flow-path optimization to enable operation over the widest possible range of Mach numbers;
active combustion control to assure continuous positive thrust (even during mode transition); robust flame-holding to maintain
stability through flow distortions; and maximized volume-to-surface area to minimize the thermal load imposed by the high-speed
engine. Thermal management plays a vital role in scramjet and combined cycle engines, including considerations for protecting
low speed propulsion systems (e.g., turbine engines) during hypersonic flight.

Efforts will enable affordable responsive strike mission by improving operability including robust operation during maneuvers and
extended operating time, improving engine performance and operations using active engine control, development of feasible
requirements for multi-mission expendable and durable hypersonic vehicle that are both achievable and fully address future
operational capability needs, as well as identify S&T investments required to address current technology gaps. Efforts will also
enable scalable and exquisite hypersonic capabilities to achieve Department priorities in hypersonics.

FY 2026 Plans:
In FY 2025 and FY 2026, the High-Speed Propulsion Integration and Demonstration effort and funding were reported in Program
Element 0603211F / Aerospace Technology Dev/Demo /Project 634926 / High Speed Systems Integ & Demo. FY 2025 funding
was $9.262 million and FY 2026 funding is $16.544 million.
FY 2027 Plans:
Continue development and integration of larger scale scramjet component technologies.
- Activities include evaluating thrust performance, structural integrity, and operability to drive higher-performance propulsion
solutions while enabling more affordable, durable, and reusable system designs.

Continue technology maturation activities to investigate, develop, and demonstrate propulsion capabilities for durable, survivable
hypersonic vehicles.


