A. Mission Description and Budget Item Justification
ABMS is the PE funding architecture and systems engineering (ASE), digital infrastructure, a suite of battle management command and control (BMC2) applications
and tools used for homeland defense and other tactical C2 mission sets, airborne connectivity (formerly known as aerial networking), deployable systems, and Beyond
Line of Sight (BLOS) long range fire & control software capability for specialized targets for the DAF's primary contribution to the Combined Joint All-Domain Command
and Control (CJADC2) warfighting concept, which the DAF formally refers to as the DAF BATTLE NETWORK. The DAF Portfolio Acquisition Executive for Command,
Control, Communication, and Battle Management (DAF PAE C3BM) has the lead role in battle management and Command and Control (C2) capabilities for the DAF.
This entails not only directing technical integration throughout the DAF but also holding acquisition authorities to develop and implement organic materiel solutions.
These solutions aim to establish resilient and widely distributable command and control capabilities within the DAF BATTLE NETWORK. The ABMS PE portfolio funds
specific interdependent programs over which the DAF PAE C3BM exercises direct oversight in terms of cost, schedule, and performance. This encompasses both the
management of these programs and the necessary architectural and systems engineering efforts to ensure effective technical coordination across the broader DAF
infrastructure.

Additionally, DAF PAE C3BM has identified an initial array of approximately 50 core programs spanning various PAEs/Program Executive Offices (PEO), whose
organizations collectively form the C3BM Enterprise. These programs represent an evolving collection of systems that, when integrated together, are pivotal in
contributing to the development of the DAF BATTLE NETWORK. Collaborating closely with the PAE/PEOs overseeing these core programs, DAF PAE C3BM
orchestrates technical integration of the DAF BATTLE NETWORK. This integration is essential to achieve the requisite operational decision advantage crucial for the
triumph of the USAF, USSF, joint, and coalition forces in the face of evolving challenges. These inter-PAE/PEO initiatives encompass a spectrum of activities, such as
technical and programmatic cooperation, comprehensive reporting, and seamless integration. With authority over technical architectures spanning the C3BM enterprise,
DAF PAE C3BM will deliver C2 capabilities.

To provide a "best of breed” capability across the DAF and facilitate accelerated delivery of the DAF BATTLE NETWORK, DAF PAE C3BM has aligned activities within
the ABMS PE portfolio with six major thrust areas:

Thrust Area 1: Architecture and Systems Engineering (ASE) and the Operational Response Team (ORT)
Thrust Area 1a ASE: Mission Domain Architecture and Mission Integration Teams: will 1) conduct Digital Engineering to support technical development activities, 2)
conduct mission domain architecture development and analysis and perform enterprise integration through domain-specific Mission Integration Teams (MITs).



