C. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                              FY 2024      FY 2025      FY 2026
Title: FORGE Command and Control (FC2)                                                                                              36.302       57.092       42.472
Description: FC2 is a Government-owned Missile Warning ground architecture that provides infrastructure, Mission Unique
Software (MUS) and sensor/spacecraft specific Command and Control (C2) capabilities that use common messaging standards
to transition C2 of the legacy Space-Based Infrared System (SBIRS) constellation, including MUS efforts developed under the
Geosynchronous Non-Integrated Tactical Warning and Attack Assessment Ops Migration to EGS (GNOME) prototype, and
integration of Next-Gen OPIR Geosynchronous Earth Orbit (NGG) and Next-Gen OPIR Polar (NGP) MUS to Future Operationally
Resilient Ground Evolution (FORGE) in order to deliver an integrated Missile Warning C2 ground system. Includes Mission

C. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                               FY 2024    FY 2025      FY 2026
Management, Telemetry Command and Control, Ground Resource Management, and user interface software development and
the integration of the Flight Dynamics software.

FY 2025 Plans:
Complete the prototype demonstration to integrate the Mission Management, Ground Resource Control Management, and user
interface software to support NGP. Award the final FC2 Phase 2 contract to continue software development of C2 to support NGP
launch, which will serve as the baseline foundation to transition SBIRS and NGG to FC2. Begin integration of the NGP MUS with
the FC2 system.
FY 2026 Plans:
Continue work on the FORGE Command and Control (FC2) prototype to integrate the Mission Management, Ground Resource
Control Management, and user interface software. Finalize the integration of NGP MUS with the FC2 system. Depending on
the maturity of the prototype and performance of the contractor there is an option to develop and integrate legacy Space-Based
InfraRed system (SBIRS) Mission Unique Software (MUS) in FY 2026.
FY 2025 to FY 2026 Increase/Decrease Statement:
The decrease of $14.620M is due to completion of competition and award to a single contractor to develop the FORGE Command
and Control (FC2) prototype. FY 2026 through 2030 funding for Next-Gen OPIR Polar (NGP) is removed as the Space Force
continues to pivot investment in the Resilient Missile Warning/Missile Tracking (MW/MT) architecture.
Title: Mission Data Processing (MDP)                                                                                               264.855    200.418        200.918
Description: The Future Operationally Resilient Ground Evolution (FORGE) MDP is a replacement for the existing legacy Space
Based Infrared System (SBIRS) Ground mission processing applications which have cyber security and scalability limitations.
MDP is creating a cyber-resilient, flexible, and scalable open framework capable of meeting current and future threats. MDP
will plan Overhead Persistent Infrared (OPIR) and other mission data resource utilization to meet warfighter requirements.
MDP provides the ability to ingest and publish varying levels of processed data for enhanced processing, perform efficient
and systematic upgrades, and orchestrate real-time wideband processing for ITW/AA and non-ITW/AA mission areas. The
MDP system provides modular mission applications to meet the future challenges of Missile Warning (MW), Missile Defense
(MD), Battlespace Awareness (BA), and Technical Intelligence (TI). MDP is critical to making cyber-secure, effective use of the
increased amounts of data that will be collected by Next-Gen OPIR.

FY 2025 Plans:
Complete development of the follow-on Mission Data Processing Applications Framework (MDPAF) effort. Continue follow-on
development and begin integration of Mission Data Processing Applications Provider (MDPAP) applications onto the FORGE
framework for SBIRS ITW/AA data processing. Continue follow-on development for Sensor Specific Processing (SSP) to support

C. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                   FY 2024    FY 2025      FY 2026
migration of all SBIRS Highly Elliptical Orbit (HEO) and Geostationary Equatorial Orbit (GEO) assets to FORGE framework. Begin
final system level integration and testing of mission data processing thrust area (MDPAF, MDPAP, and SSP) for SBIRS transition
to operations on FORGE. Begin the DevSecOps pipeline to be responsive to evolving threats. Rapidly respond to implement
system resiliency and situational awareness necessary to operate in the contested space domain. Activities may include, but are
not limited to program office support, studies, technical analysis, experimentation, prototyping, and activities that may leverage
commercial and international opportunities.
FY 2026 Plans:
Continue follow-on development and complete integration of MDPAP application onto the FORGE Framework for SBIRS ITW/
AA data processing. MDPAF to close out end of FY2025, and Enterprise OPIR Solution (EOS) to be the new contract in place
starting FY2026. Complete final system level integration and testing of mission data processing thrust area (EOS, MDPAP,
and SSP) for SBIRS transition to operations on FORGE. Further develop the DevSecOps pipeline to be responsive to evolving
threats. Develop and implement plans to integrate Medium Earth Orbit (MEO)/ Low Earth Orbit (LEO) sensor data from MEO
Epochs and Space Development Agency (SDA) Tranches. Rapidly respond to implement system resiliency and situational
awareness necessary to operate in the contested space domain. Activities include, but are not limited to program office support,
studies, technical analysis, experimentation, risk reduction, prototyping, and activities that may leverage commercial, U.S.
Government partnership, and international opportunities to respond to existing and emerging adversarial threats with speed and
agility.
FY 2025 to FY 2026 Increase/Decrease Statement:
Increase of $0.500M is due to inflation rate adjustment.
Title: Next-Gen Transition                                                                                                             150.757    166.951         65.360
Description: Next-Gen transition is the development to enable use of Future Operationally Resilient Ground Evolution (FORGE)
for mission processing and Command and Control (C2) for future Overhead Persistent Infrared (OPIR) space systems. Included in
this effort is the development of Next Gen Interim Ops (NIO) to ensure the most critical ground processing is ready in time for the
first Next-Gen OPIR Geostationary Equatorial Orbit (GEO) satellite launch as required by Joint Requirements Oversight Council
Memorandum (JROCM) 130-17. NIO will create mono tracks and publish those mono tracks to the existing Space Based Infrared
System
(SBIRS) Block 20 ground system for fusion and dissemination to the warfighter.

FY 2025 Plans:

C. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                        FY 2024    FY 2025      FY 2026
Continue development and integration of the mission unique software needed for C2 for Next-Gen OPIR Geosynchronous Earth
Orbit (NGG) and Next-Gen OPIR Polar (NGP). Continue integration of multiple mission data processing applications into the
framework to support NGG and NGP.
FY 2026 Plans:
Finalize and integrate the mission unique software needed for C2, NGG and NGP. Continue integration of multiple mission data
processing applications into the framework to support NGG and NGP.
FY 2025 to FY 2026 Increase/Decrease Statement:
Decrease of $101.591M is due to completion of NGG 5K testing in FY 2025. FY 2026 focuses on C2 integration. FY 2026 through
2030 funding for Next-Gen OPIR Polar (NGP) is removed as the Space Force continues to pivot investment in the Resilient
Missile Warning/Missile Tracking (MW/MT) architecture.
Title: Relay Ground Station - Asia (RGS-A)                                                                                                   42.519     65.134         24.531
Description: Overhead Persistent Infrared (OPIR) data collected in space must be relayed to ground entry points and routed to
provide warfighters with timely information. The legacy Space Based Infrared System (SBIRS) ground architecture requires RGS
upgrades and new RGSs to receive OPIR data from legacy and future Next-Gen OPIR assets. This effort will provide data to the
Mission Control Station (MCS) for processing and dissemination to warfighters and National Command Authorities. The RGS
modernization effort will include the ability to operate antennas and process data. This activity is for the Asia ground station portion
of the Future Operationally Resilient Ground Evolution (FORGE) - RGS architecture and includes up to 4 antennas. It is currently
an ACAT III program that will be re-categorized to an ACAT II program which includes additional sites beyond RGS-A.

FY 2025 Plans:
Complete final system installation and checkout.
FY 2026 Plans:
Complete antenna installation at Camp Blaz, Guam. Integrate communication and cryptological equipment. Conduct initial and
final qualification tests for Relay Ground Station (RGS) antennas. Activate the Relay Ground Station - Asia (RGS-A) site.
FY 2025 to FY 2026 Increase/Decrease Statement:
Decrease of $40.603M is due to all non-recurring engineering, enterprise modem design and delivery, and most facilities and
infrastructure work completed in FY 2025.
Title: Relay Ground Stations (RGSs)                                                                                                           1.442     10.800         25.049
Description: Overhead Persistent Infrared (OPIR) data collected in space must be relayed to ground entry points and routed
to provide warfighters with timely information. The legacy Space Based Infrared System (SBIRS) ground architecture requires
RGS upgrades and new RGSs to receive OPIR data from legacy and future Next-Gen OPIR assets. This effort expands the RGS

C. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                     FY 2024    FY 2025      FY 2026
system to two additional sites that will use common hardware capable of supporting all Next Gen-OPIR space assets. This effort
will provide data to the Mission Control Station (MCS) for processing and dissemination to warfighters and National Command
Authorities. The RGS modernization effort will include the ability to operate antennas, process data, and support older Defense
Support Program (DSP) assets. This activity is for RGSs not included in the RGS-A portion of the Future Operationally Resilient
Ground Evolution (FORGE) - RGS architecture. All RGS activities will be consolidated with RGS-A to capture the RGS system as
as an ACAT II program.

FY 2025 Plans:
Continue second site, Relay Ground Station South (RGS-S), development and integration activities. Award third RGS site RGS
United Kingdom (UK), which includes purchasing ITW/AA-class antenna and associated hardware for the Next-Gen Constellation.
Execute site preparations.
FY 2026 Plans:
Complete site specific environmental work and award Task Order for procurement, installation, and test for RGS antennas. Finish
design for support facilities and infrastructure, begin construction of communication shelters, ring walls, and complete installation
of networking and telecommunications equipment.
FY 2025 to FY 2026 Increase/Decrease Statement:
Increase of $14.249M is due to three RGS sites in construction simultaneously.
                                                                                 Accomplishments/Planned Programs Subtotals              495.875    500.395        358.330$$, $$$$, $$N/A
Remarks$$, $$The Next-Gen Overhead Persistent Infrared (OPIR) Ground program is executing an acquisition strategy using Middle Tier of Acquisition (MTA) authority for Rapid
Prototyping approved via Acquisition Decision Memorandum on 5 Dec 19. The program will transition to the software acquisition pathway at the end of the MTA.

To support this acquisition strategy, the program will follow an agile approach to develop capabilities and a robust DevSecOps (Development/Security/Operations)
solution to deliver the capabilities. The Future Operationally Resilient Ground Evolution (FORGE) program is pursuing a rapid prototyping approach founded primarily
on software and infrastructure reuse, partnerships with other programs, limited scope, use of existing contracts where necessary, and maximizing competition where
possible. For the Mission Data Processing (MDP) thrust, the FORGE program is using competitive use Other Transaction (OT) authorities to develop the framework and
the applications. For the FORGE Command and Control (FC2) thrust, the FORGE team is using competitive use OT authorities to develop the Mission Management,
Telemetry Command and Control, Ground Resource Management, and user interface software, while the mission unique software will be provided by the space

 vehicle contractors. For the Next-Gen Transition effort, the program is using the Next-Gen Geostationary Equatorial Orbit (GEO) and Next-Gen Polar contract with the
 space vehicle prime contractor to perform the work needed to develop the ground capabilities. The program is executing the MDP, FC2, and Next-Gen OPIR Interim
